\subsection*{The Dreamlands}

Within her dreams a Princess travels beyond her mind and into the very soul of humanity. Within the Dreamlands the hopes and aspirations of mankind take life, they form vast cities. Beautiful vistas with all the incomprehensible forms of a dream. The Dreamlands are more than just a metaphor; they are a true world. The inhabitants have lives, hopes and dwell in functional societies. Many Princesses are surprised to discover something so ordinary amongst dreams and flights of fancy, but is it really so surprising than a Princess' dreams would form after how she sees the world? For the Princess who cares so much about friendship and community when she is awake, what else would she dream about? 

Travelling to the Dreamlands offers many practical advantages to a Princess; she can find friends and mentors among the population including the Radiant Queens. Objects of power, often created and traded by Dreamlanders, can be formed into Bequests. However the Dreamlands is not just frolicking and sunshine; it contains all mankind's fears and hates as well as it's hopes and dreams; and it was once used by the Darkness to construct a trap for the souls of the Kingdom. Though the trap is broken it's creaky machinery and the remnant of the prison's old wardens still seek to imprison the Enlightened in a blissful dream. 

\section*{Culture}

The Nobility are really good at community; in the short time since the Release a sprawling culture has grown across a network of blogs, forums and social networking sites. The Hopeful community covers more than just Princesses; Beacons and Sworn are welcome and even ordinary people can often be found on the comment threads. The online Radiant community is hardly a walled garden; it spills forth onto related subjects. Princesses can often be found bogging about and arguing in forums related to art, politics, current affairs, activism and social justice. Many blogs or forums are considered to be both hubs of the Radiant community \textendash\, for the author or prominent members are Princesses \textendash\, and considered to be ordinary websites by their mundane viewers \textendash\, for the Princesses are still in the closet (at least under this username). 

Many Princesses eagerly flock to debates about occult theory or magical phenomena, but on this subject the Nobility often retreat to their own private communities for a Princess talking about her emotional variety of magic often causes her to clash with both mortals \textendash\, who eagerly latch onto occult principles (accurate or otherwise) to make up for the fact they cannot perform magic \textendash\, and actual magicians \textendash\, for whom occult principles form the foundation of their power \textendash\, some young and naive princesses have caught the attention of experienced magicians who simply recognised the way they talk and think about magic. 

Inevitably debates between so many young, passionate ideologues often descends into a morass of arguments. Since Princesses are almost invariably socially competent these arguments are, if not productive, at least good at getting Princesses to think from multiple points of view. People often wonder how Princesses, a group who live by the maxim \textquotedblleft School, friends, royal duties, sleep, choose three\textquotedblright\, ever find the time to argue on the internet. In truth it's common for Princesses to vanish entirely from their online community when an actual problem comes to their town; lives have even been saved because somebody decided check up why a someone stopped posting. 

Perhaps the most practical use of the Princess' online culture is when it move offline; regional meet ups are common enough and even international get together can be held in an easily reached location within the Dreamlands, such as a Queen's domain. These events help build a Princess' collection of emergency phone numbers and can lead to the formation of Nakamas. The internet and the Dreamlands is in fact one of the most common ways for a lone Princess to find herself a Nakama, often beginning with a message like \textquotedblleft Looking for Nakama in San Francisco\textquotedblright\, posted on a website or left with a royal page.

\subsection*{Language}

The Hopeful are for the most part a young culture and even the parts of it that regularly communicate don't have any formal body to standardise language. While there is a linguistic legacy that predates the Release, three in fact: One is in the Royal Tongue (which many Princesses find cumbersome, or just annoying) another is in Alhambran (which many Radiant refuse to use on principle), the third comes from the Embassy to the Dreamlands (which is specialised and relatively obscure). Consequently the Radiant use a fast changing system of slang, memes and technical terms that vary across geographical regions and even parts of the internet. The language of the Radiant is young enough that most words can easily be traced back to their origin. The following terms are usually used by Princesses in the anglosphere, having been spread across that portion of the internet. Some of the more specific terms are unique to American Princesses. 

The tradition of naming Queens after playing cards came early after Princesses searched for an alternative to the Queen's titles in the Royal Tongue. The Queen of Diamonds suggested \textquotedblleft The Queen of Diamonds\textquotedblright\, (as well as \textquotedblleft The Crystal-eyed One\textquotedblright ) as a two very rough summaries of her most important titles. One of the Princesses present at the time started referring to the other Queens with different playing cards, since none of the other Queens had made English suggestions yet (or been asked yet, this happened quite early) it stuck. There are actually several alternative card based naming schemes, most attempt to try and match the Queens to card based symbolism. Either through their invocation's element or by trying to match their character to a feudal class. Neither are popular, partly because the symbolism doesn’t work too well, partly because if the symbolism of playing cards has any useful magical property it's for non-Princess magic, and 
partly because the Queen of Diamonds prefers to be called the Queen of Diamonds. The common system is found throughout the English speaking world. Different naming schemes can be found elsewhere, but it is more common for each Queen to offer a set of unrelated rough translations into the local language. 

Terms in Japanese originate from Bonnie Getsuei, an American (and complete Japanophile) who forged much of the Radiant's community in San Francisco and even provided a common entry point to the online Radiant community for English speaking princesses (presumably actual Japanese Princesses also use their native tongue). 

Italian words can often trace their origin to the Queen of Heart's earliest followers in the United Kingdom (The Court of Hearts had a late start in America, as the first impressions of that court often clash with America's national ideals. Today few Princesses even remember what the fuss was about.) Influenced by Andartan culture those Princesses chose to use a romance language, and since they didn't want to use French; Princesses everywhere sprinkle their magic with Italian terms. 

Greek and Latin words both share origins in the Court of Diamonds; the early Lights were the first to attempt to begin classifying and studying hopeful magic and related phenomena. This project was split between those who were more influenced by their Queen and wanted to use Greek and those who were more influenced by human academia and wanted to use Latin. The argument was never settled and various words from both languages have become part of the Princess lexicon, mostly for things a Princess can go a while without encountering as everything else was named through informal, and therefore faster, channels. Exceptionally nerdy Princesses sometimes use Greek instead of the Latin terms or Latin instead of the Greek, and Latin or Greek instead of English, Italian and Japanese terms. 

The Embassy to the Dreamlands, perhaps the only lasting Radiant organisation to exist through the Long Night, tended to use names taken from people both living, Dreamlander and even fictional (note that the three are rarely distinct categories). Few of these terms are still in use. 

Finally English is, obviously, the de-facto language of English speaking Princesses. Anything that did not get a catchy enough name quickly enough is likely to be in English. One unusual, and uniquely American, fact about English is that many Princesses adopt a more \textquotedblleft royal\textquotedblright\, manner of speaking in their Transformed identity, which is to say a British accent ranging from \textquotedblleft BBC English\textquotedblright\ to \textquotedblleft not even The Queen lays it on that thick\textquotedblright. Princesses who are actually from the United Kingdom usually use their natural accent, though as the British will parody anything some have been known to play up, or adopt, incomprehensible regional accents when around Americans. 

\subsection*{Cliques}

Princesses who live near to each other rarely remain strangers for long. A new Princess is often eager to meet peers who can help her master her new magical abilities and provide support in dealing with the new dangers she faces from both within and without. While tracking down a newly Blossomed Princess' mundane identity is near universally considered to be horrific behaviour beneath all but the Court of Tears, no such taboo exists against making contact with her Transformed identity so Princesses usually seek out the company of their fellow Nobles. Usually it is not much trouble for a new Princess to contact her predecessors. A large community of Princesses creates a wealth of rumours and urban legends to investigate (online or offline). It is even easier for an experienced Princess to find a newbie. In cities where there is an established Princess population there's usually more than enough people plugged into the social grapevine (or prone to prophetic dreams) to notice the waves a new Princess makes, 
and there’s plenty of magical tricks that can be applied to finding another Princesses. 

In smaller towns without an established Princess community it is still practical for the local Nobles to find each other if they all invest time and effort. But even here meetings between freshly Blossomed Nobles aren't left to chance. It is common for Princesses Blossoming apart from an established Noble community to meet guide shortly before or after Blossoming. Earlier Princesses often met an animal that’s clearly tame but not obviously owned, and is more intelligent than other beasts of its kind. But animal guides are increasingly rare in favour of living dolls or plushies. In the Hopeful community these magical teachers and companions are named Shikigami, they are the souls of prominent citizens from the Kingdom and can offer both their experience and prophetic dreams (how else could they find a Princess before she Blossoms) to their new students; and of course they introduce their students to each other.

And once a new Princess has been introduced to the community, it's only natural for her to start making friends; as a rule Princesses are sociable and agreeable. And so, in a city with a large Princess population friendship Cliques will inevitably form. 

Cliques are just what the name implies, friendship groups. They go shopping, see movies, plait each other’s hair or compete in fun magic contests. There is no obligation that a Clique will work together to fulfil their duties. A Grace may find that of the local Princesses she has the most in common with a Champion and a Troubadour, they share tastes in books, balls, and boys, so even though they might disagree on politics or the most effective way to help the city they still seek each other out when there is a new film to watch or a formal dance to attend. But when it's time to work the Grace goes campaigning with people who share her Beliefs and politics, be they Nobles or mortals.  

Many Cliques go out of their way to avoid \textquotedblleft talking shop\textquotedblright . The primary purpose of a Clique is to help Princesses de-stress and recharge after the pressures of the job by providing friends who understand what it means to be a Princess and know when to (and have the power to) force a Princess to get a good nights sleep \textendash\, no ands, ifs or buts. If the two Graces in a Clique are supporting rival political parties then getting into political debates can ruin what should be a relaxing night (or it can be fun and invigorating). While Nobles usually have the social skills to avoid getting into an unwanted argument, part of those skills involve knowing when a Clique should have a rule against talking shop.

However when Princesses are reacting to a problem: Be it the Darkness, the Twilight Queens or something mundane like an earthquake, and a Princess' usual co-workers aren't sufficient a Clique is usually her second point of call for backup. Members of a Clique trust each other, know each other well enough to work well together, and of course they all have each other's phone numbers. 

\subsection*{Nakama}

Not all Princesses have the choice or the desire to distinguish between their friends and their co-workers. For these Princesses a Nakama serves as an alternative to a Clique. The word \textquotedblleft Nakama\textquotedblright\, means a group of friends; translated into English you might say \textquotedblleft buddies\textquotedblright\, or \textquotedblleft gang\textquotedblright\, in the playful kids' use of the word. Among the Nobility (if they aren’t Japanese) Nakama has a more restricted sense: a small group of Nobles who joined together or were thrown together (perhaps all Blossoming in the same town, or facing the same great crisis) and have become something very close to a family because of it. They share more than the Hopeful’s duty - they intertwine their mundane lives, as well as their Noble calling. Many Nakama go so far as to share their mundane identity, especially if they wish to live together to save on rent or pool their magic into creating a magically defended home. 

While more city Princesses are in Cliques than Nakama in small towns and rural areas the reverse is true. If there's only one Champion in town, and she's too new to have found or trained reliable mortal fighters to work with, the only backup she can call upon on is the other local Princesses. A Mender is perfectly capable of learning the same battle magic as a Champion if she puts her mind to it. So with sufficient motivation the problems that cause a Clique to avoid talking shop can be overcome allowing just about any group of Radiant Princesses to function as a Nakama. 

A Nakama can include the actual families of the Nobles, as well as their Nakama in the Japanese sense - people with no trace of magic in them, but who are intimate parts of the Nobles’ mundane lives. This is especially common if the Nakama was formed in response to a common threat, as Princesses are very defensive of their loved ones and if the only way to convince someone that monsters are real and they're infesting this town is to reveal your secret; then you may as well go a bit further and bring them into the Nakama's communal home where there's usually a Princess around to keep an eye out for danger and magical defences. 

\subsection*{Campaigns}

Princesses may spend most of their time disagreeing with each other about how to improve the world, and even about what a better world would even look like, but in the face to a true emergency they are quick to put their differences aside and unite behind a Campaign.

A Campaign always starts when Princesses face a large problem where the solution is obvious and unambiguous to the Radiant. In a long career a Princess might see Campaigns against large Darkspawn incursions or to rebuild after natural disasters but not for more complicated problems where every political ideology has it's own mutually opposing solution. 

The concept of a Campaign is well known, and most begin deliberately. Princesses announce that there will be a meeting in a Queen's palace (usually the Queen of Hearts) at a certain time and see if enough people turn up. It is generally considered a bad sign if only one Noble starts trying to arrange a Campaign, if a problem doesn't convince several Nobles they need to start a campaign it is unlikely to convince a large group of Nobles they should join a campaign. Of course, this rule of thumb depends on the size of the local Princess population. 

A Queen's palace not chosen just because it's a convenient meeting point, the gathered Radiant ask the Queen to select a Campaign's leader and officers. Even Princesses with an ideological commitment to democracy, and there are a lot of them, usually agree that if a Queen can't pick a leader who's acceptable to everyone then this issue isn't the sort of direct problem suitable for a campaign and it would be better for Nobles to work on solving the issue in their own way than spend their time arguing about how to solve the issue. 

A Campaign rarely formally end when it achieves it's aim. Usually the leader begin expanding the Campaign's scope and ideology, after the Darkspawn are chased out she turns to improving things to prevent new Taint forming. Once this happens Princesses who disagree with the new direction quickly depart, usually the Court of Spades leave first and serve as the proverbial canary in the coal mine. This happens so often that it's become a running joke among the Radiant and Campaigns that do formally disband after achieving their aims often announce their end with a bombastic speech announcing a radical expansion of their mission, followed by a prank or heckling from the Spades. It's not unusual for the Princesses who didn't depart a completed Campaign to become a Nakama, but it's considered a worrying sign when a Princess insists she is still the leader after everyone's departed or tries to prevent people from leaving

\subsection*{Principalities}

In the slang of the Nobility a Principality once refereed to organisations run by a Princess, over time this definition has become looser and can now be used to refer to any organisation where the Princess has notable status or influence, or even an organisation where a Princess is working hard to acquire influence.  As Princesses consider themselves human and part of human society rather than any secret Noble society Principalities are regular mortal institutions rather than secret organisations hidden from those unaware of the Nobel world. Any type of organisation can be a Principality. They include public corporations with a charitable ethos, voluntary groups, government bodies, law enforcement, music producers, and more. 

Just as the Clique or the Nakama is the standard building block of Noble social life, the Principality is the standard unit of Noble work life. When Princesses with similar duties organise to share their workload and pool their resources they typically do so through a Principality. Since Princesses consider themselves human and part of human society they see no reason not to join mortal organisations who've already set up the infrastructure needed for the task and when Princesses with similar goals sit down to discuss how to avoid wasting time by working the same case sooner or later someone will point out that they should also avoid wasting time on a case that mortals have covered. Many Princesses also consider it a moral duty to work within the system, particularly if their role involves wielding authority over other people. 

In size Principalities range just as widely as they do in structure. At their smallest you'll find groups with less than ten members such as a Champion leading a cell of mortal monster hunters against the Darkness. Or a pub that serves as the hub of the local community. At their largest Principalities can work on an international scale. However despite speculation that every popular public figure is the mundane identity of a Princess most large Principalities are of the \textquotedblleft working hard to acquire influence \textquotedblright\, verity.

While acquiring a Principality is a common Aspiration for Princesses of any Court or Calling Graces notably the most likely Calling to seek out their own Principality. Among the Queens it is unsurprisingly the Court of Hearts who are most interested. A Heart of any Calling is as likely to be involved in a Principality as a Grace of any other Court. After the Court of Hearts, the Court of Diamonds is the second most interested

Typically the membership of a Principality skewed heavily towards the mundane members, this is not because Princesses avoid Noble rivals for influence, quite the contrary, it is simply because regular mortals are far more common than Princesses, Sworn and Beacons combined. To the Nobility a bias towards fellow Princesses is seen as low behaviour befitting only the Court of Mirrors, and so even though most Princesses do have at least some bias (Blossoming is a very accurate judge of character even if Princesses can fall from grace later in life, and magical abilities are a useful advantage to any organisation) they still gladly accept mortals into their employment. After that numbers alone ensure that all but the smallest Principality where it's feasible to make the entire Membership Sworn will soon be full of regular mortals. 

Conflict between Principalities is inevitable. They often compete for resources or have fundamentally opposed methods or goals, after all both the Democratic and Republican party (or their youth branches) are full of Princesses hoping to get the Presidency in a few decades time. Typically these conflicts are civilised and fought with debates and campaigning but even the most vicious conflicts between two Radiant led Principalities rarely fall below the level of slander and obstructionism. 

% Among the Courts of Diamonds and Hearts accusing someone of being more interested in winning a conflict than fulfilling their duties is an almost unforgivable insult, it is practically an accusation that someone has the same attitude as the Court of Storms. Among the Court of Swords it is if anything even worse. Swords are supposed to follow their passions, so to suggest her passions are leading her astray is to suggest she is in some ways fundamentally broken as a person. 

% However Princesses can and do let their emotions get the better of them and Princesses who put themselves into positions that require conflict without demonstrating they have some way of handling their emotions, such as a superhuman Composure, self awareness, or a Nakama to keep them grounded, often make other Radiant nervous. They're not likely to directly hurt people, but they can create no end of delays or bad policies; then again they're just as likely to end up clearing the air through a harmless magic fight or a passionate and volatile romance with their opposite number. 

\subsection*{The Twilight Courts}

Among the Nobility there is no agreed way to help the world. Princesses who advocate for collective solutions spar across the debating stage with Nobles who focus upon individual liberty. In laboratories Princesses push the boundaries of technology while on the other side of the university campus their peers argue for a return to the good old ways. But among the Nobility an informal understanding holds, to Princesses it's so natural and obvious that nobody gave it a name. The understanding states that even when you disagree with a fellow Radiant's idea of a better world you can still respect her as a person, and while her utopia may not be yours it is at least better than a world shrouded by the Darkness. 

But this understanding only holds to the Radiant. No such benefit of the doubt is given to the Twilight Courts. 

The Twilight Courts are thrice separated from the Radiant. They are separated by politics, the Radiant and Twilight courts will at best clench their teeth and swallow their distaste before teaming up against a mutual foe and at worst violently oppose each other. They are separated by magic, for the five Radiant Queens are neighbours in the Dreamlands and their Invocations demand nothing more than virtuous behaviour as each Queen defines it. The three Twilight Queens each exist alone and their Invocations take a toll upon the user's mind, body, or soul. Finally they are separated by morality, for the philosophies of the Twilight Courts directly harm innocents in a way that the Radiant Courts do not (The Court of Mirrors is more complicated, and so it is sometimes held to be on the Radiant side). Thus even the most inexperienced Princess cannot help but see that there is a division between Radiant and Twilight on the deepest levels.

And though the five Radiant Queens and their Courts stand together. No such camaraderie exists amongst the Twilight Courts: The Courts of Tears and Storms have been in open war for perhaps as long as they have existed. And the harsh dogmatic outlook of those two Courts means that they are less tolerant of the Court of Mirrors than Radiant Princesses. Each Twilight Court stands in isolation or with the Radiant. 

But perhaps the deepest reason for conflict between the Radiant and Twilight Courts is that for once even Nobles want to remain in conflict. Alone or among their trusted friends the Radiant admit that a part of them is tempted by the philosophies of the Twilight Courts. What Princess hasn't put her beloved sister's needs above a stranger's? Felt hatred for the Darkness' evil? Clung a little too hard to a reassuring Belief or assumed a fellow Radiant is good and virtuous when they first met just because she's Noble? And when the Radiant reject the part of them that's tempted to walk down that long road paved with good intentions they also reject their kinship to every Princess who's walked that road to the very end. 

For all their light, Princesses are still human and think in very human ways. 

\subsection*{Queens}

Every Princess knows that to make the world better she must improve herself, she must rise to the challenge. And every Princess knows that if she works hard enough and holds faith in herself she can become so much better. For every Princess holds the potential to become a Queen, a woman of light and magic as far beyond a Princess as a Princess is beyond a mortal.

It is not known exactly how many Queens (or Kings) once ruled the domains of the Kingdom, of this unknown number only eight Queens still have the power to affect the world. Of this eight: Five are dead, one is living, another is presumed to be living, and one is... Transformed. Collectively the five dead Queens are known as the Radiant, for they remain loyal to the light in spirit as well as word, for centuries the Radiant Queens were trapped deep within the Dreamlands, but now their trap has fallen. From their Palaces within the Dreamlands they call out to Princesses, seeking Hopeful agents who will restore the Light upon Earth. 

The Queens are the linchpins of Hopeful society in more ways than one. Each Queen is a living (or otherwise, these days) font of magic. Her Beliefs have become a coloured mirror that shines additional Light onto the world; everyone who shares her ideals can draw upon the Queen's Invocation to gain greater power or unlock new abilities that they would not otherwise have been possible. Only the most supplicant Princesses define their beliefs entirely by the Queen they follow; but all Princesses take the time to study the Queen's philosophies and draw both magic and inspiration from the principles with which they agree. For while many Princesses believe in the importance of community, none can speak on the topic with the experience and wisdom of the Queen of Hearts. Even when a Princess disagrees with a Queen or grows beyond the beliefs of her mentor as she develops, she is still likely to use the Queen's ideals and philosophies as a foundation; for the only way to see further than a giant is to stand atop her 
royal shoulders. 

While no Queen is capable of using her full power on Earth. The five Radiant Queens are dead, the Queen of Tears will not leave Alhambra, the Queen of Storms will not abandon her battle in the Dark World, and while nobody knows what is up with the Queen of Mirrors it is generally accepted that she doesn't act directly. The Queens can still provide advice and guidance. They are people who have built and won the hearts of nations. As monarchs and rulers they were perhaps the very best in all of history; their Kingdoms may have fallen but all kingdoms fall in time, few were utopian at their apex. As mentors and teachers the Radiant Queens have more to often than a young Princess could imagine.  